<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-134-271 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 814 724</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  June 6 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>1st Step in cross-platform software by OSF. (Open SoftwareFoundation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rohrbough, Linda.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Open Software FoundationProduct DevelopmentCompilersStandardizationOpen Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>1ST STEP IN CROSS-PLATFORM SOFTWARE BY OSF 06/06/91 SAN JOSE, CALIFORNIA,U.S.A., 1991 JUN 6 (NB) -- The Open Software Foundation (OSF) announced ithas selected TDF, a compiler intermediate language, as the first step indeveloping the Architecture-Neutral Distribution Format (ANDF).andP;  Today, usersmust purchase and install a different version of each application for eachcomputer architecture they own, but the OSF wants to change all that.andM;The idea here is to develop standards for software so developers can developand distribute applications that will work on a variety of differentcomputers, the (OSF) said.andM;OSF issued a request for technology (RFT) in April to explore thepossibilities of efficiently developing and distributing software that isindependent of the hardware architecture.andP;  15 qualifying technologiesresponded to the RFT, and commercial feasibility tests were conducted at thesame time the technologies were looked at technically, OSF said.andM;&quot;ANDF addresses one of the industry's oldest problems; applicationportability on multiple hardware architectures,&quot; said Pat Riemitis, OSFbusiness area manager.andP;  &quot;ANDF will help drive the growth of the open systemsmarket and provide software developers with a cost effective means to developand distribute their applications for a wide variety of architectures.&quot;andM;TDF, from the Electronics Division of the Defense Research Agency, wasdesigned for working on a variety of hardware platforms from its inception,OSF said.andP;  TDF supports ANSI C, and has been designed to support a wide rangeof programming languages, such as C++, COBOL and FORTRAN, said the OSF.andM;(Linda Rohrbough/19910606/Press Contact: Donna Ruane, Open SoftwareFoundation, Tel: 617/621-8772, Fax:)</TEXT></DOC>